Using implicit differentiation with respect to \emph{x}, we see that

\begin{align*}
\frac{dy}{dx} &= \frac{d}{dx} (xy + x^2 + 1) \\
&= (1 \cdot y + x \cdot \frac{d}{dx} \, y) + 2x + 0 \\
&= y + x \, \frac{dy}{dx} + 2x \\
&= \frac{y + 2x}{1 - x} \end{align*}

and substituting in the point $\displaystyle (-1,1)$, we have

\begin{align*}
\frac{dy}{dx} &= \frac{y + 2x}{1 - x} \\
&= \frac{1 + 2(-1)}{1 - (-1)} = \frac{-1}{2} \end{align*}

We use the slope-point formula to determine that the equation of the
tangent line at $\displaystyle (-1,1)$ is given by

\begin{align*} 
y - 1 &= \frac{-1}{2} (x - (-1)) \\
y - 1 &= \frac{-1}{2} x - \frac{1}{2} \\
y &= {\color{blue} \frac{-1}{2} x + \frac{1}{2}}\end{align*}
